## üìù Key Points

### Must Have
- Mobile-first responsive design
- Sufficient color contrast (minimum 4.5:1 for text)
- Consistent spacing system (4px or 8px grid)
- Clear visual hierarchy
- Accessible keyboard navigation
- Fast loading and perceived performance

### Do
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Implement consistent design patterns
- Provide immediate feedback on interactions
- Test on real devices and screen sizes
- Follow WCAG **2.2 AA** guidelines minimum (2.1 AA baseline where needed)
- Respect user preferences (reduced motion, color scheme)

### Don't
- Don't sacrifice accessibility for aesthetics
- Don't ignore mobile users (mobile traffic is often the majority)
- Don't use color alone to convey information
- Don't create interactions that work only on desktop
- Don't block users with unnecessary features (auto-play, popups)
- Don't ignore performance impact of design decisions

## üîß Testing Checklist

Before launching, verify:
- [ ] Works on mobile devices (iOS Safari, Android Chrome)
- [ ] Keyboard navigation works throughout
- [ ] Screen reader can access all content
- [ ] Color contrast meets WCAG AA standards
- [ ] Forms have clear labels and validation
- [ ] Loading states are shown for async operations
- [ ] Hover states also work for keyboard focus
- [ ] Touch targets are at least 44√ó44px
- [ ] Page loads in under 3 seconds on 3G
- [ ] Animations respect `prefers-reduced-motion`

---

**Remember**: Good UX/UI is invisible - users should accomplish their goals effortlessly without noticing the interface. Prioritize usability over aesthetics, accessibility over novelty, and user needs over designer preferences.
